Can I use "no hou ga" when I compare several things?
by Svensk » Thu 06.25.2009 3:39 am Hello!=)First I want to say that my active knowledge (I think it is called active knowledge, correct me if I am wrong)) of the english language is not very good, though my passive knowledge is quite good, so please excuse me if I am not clear enough! I have a question about the japanese grammar, that I hope you can answer. When I ask which of two alternatives is more, I say; "X to Y to dochira no hoo ga Z desu ka?" and when I ask about three or more things I say "X to Y to Z to dare/doko/dore ga ichiban A desu ka?", BUT, and this is my question, can I say ..."dare/doko/dore no hoo ga....", or is it simply wrong? I hope that you all have patience with my understanding of the english language, and I am sorry if I am to confusing.Thanks!
Life sucks, then you die.
